"Modrzyński J., Eriksson G.","Response of Picea abies populations from elevational transects in the Polish Sudety and Carpathian mountains to simulated drought stress",2002,"Forest Ecology and Management","165","1-3",,"105","116",,,10.1016/S0378-1127(01)00651-X,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037099772&partnerID=40&md5=bec19defe6b92a42f27841b57d05f2fa","Department of Silviculture, Faculty of Forestry, Agricultural University of Poznan, Wojska Polskiego 69, Pl 60-625 Poznan, Poland; Department of Forest Genetics, Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences, Box 7027, S-750 07 Uppsala, Sweden","Modrzyński, J., Department of Silviculture, Faculty of Forestry, Agricultural University of Poznan, Wojska Polskiego 69, Pl 60-625 Poznan, Poland; Eriksson, G., Department of Forest Genetics, Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences, Box 7027, S-750 07 Uppsala, Sweden","The response of 24 Norway spruce populations from a broad elevational gradient to four combinations of watering and temperature was studied in a phytotron experiment. The results of this experiment are important for better understanding possible impacts of global warming on low- and high-altitude populations of Picea abies. The investigated populations showed evidence of clinal variation in height, mass and bud-set parameters in all treatments. The higher the elevation of origin, the earlier the bud-set and the poorer the mass and height of the populations. The interaction of population origin x treatment showed a small percentage variance component, but there was a clear differentiation in reaction of the tested populations to the simulated drought. The low-altitude populations showed a strong negative reaction to the drought stress, whereas the high-altitude ones were more drought tolerant. So if global warming would be accompanied by soil drought, the low-altitude populations would reduce their growth much more than the high-altitude ones. But if global warming would be combined with an adequate increase of precipitation, then low-altitude populations would profit from this climate change more than high-altitude ones. © 2002 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.","Biomass partitioning; Bud-set; Growth; Norway spruce; Temperature; Watering","Computer simulation; Drought; Global warming; Precipitation (meteorology); Drought stresses; Forestry; altitude; biomass allocation; climate change; drought stress; global warming; growth; temperature; Poland; Abies; Picea; Picea abies",,,,,,"Bouvarel, P., Observations sur la date de l'autement de quelques provenances francaises d'epicea (1971) Ann. Ec. Eaux For. Nancy, 18 (1), pp. 96-129; Bouvarel, P., L'adaptation écologique des arbres forestiers. Application á la sélection (1974) Ecologie forestiere, pp. 155-173. , Pesson, P. (Ed.). Gautther-Villars, Paris; Bulmer, M.G., (1980) The Mathematical Theory of Quantitative Genetics, p. 255. , Oxford University Press, Oxford; Carey, E.V., DeLucia, E.H., Ball, J.T., Stem maintenance and construction respiration in Pinus ponderosa grown in different concentrations of atmospheric CO 2 (1996) Tree Physiol., 16, pp. 125-130; Carey, E.V., Callaway, R.M., DeLucia, E.H., Stem respiration of Ponderosa pines grown in contrasting climates: Implications for global climate change (1997) Oekologia, 111 (1), pp. 19-25; Chomicz, K., Samej, F., Stosunki opadowe (1974) Klima Tatier, pp. 443-536. , Koncek, M. (Ed.). Vyd. Slov. Akad. Vied, Bratislava; Dormling, I., Photoperiodic control of growth cessation in Norway spruce seedlings (1973) Proceedings of the IUFRO, WP 2.01.4, Symp. Dormancy in Trees, pp. 1-16. , Kórnik; Dormling, I., Influence of light intensity and temperature on photoperiodic response of Norway spruce provenances (1979) Proc. IUFRO, Joint Meet. Work. Part., Norway spruce provenances and Norway spruce breeding, pp. 398-408. , Bucharest 1979, Escherode; Ellenberg, H., (1978) Vegetation Mitteleuropas mit den Alpen in ökologischer Sicht, p. 981. , Verlag Eugen Ulm